alfe-plugin-model — V2 plugin contract + EPURE as the first consumer
====================================================================

See also: alfe.plan ("V2 / out of scope here" bullet),
issues/closed/alfe-cli.issue (the parsed-but-inert --epure flag),
issues/closed/alfe-backend-bricscad.issue section 7,
issues/closed/alfe-backend-autocad.issue section 4,
spec section "Exposed helpers" (the *AUTOLISP-* hook surface a
plugin can read).

Context
-------

alfe today carries the *flag* surface of a plugin model — --epure
is parsed, stored in `options-epure-p`, mirrored via
$AUTOLISP_EPURE, and surfaces in `--help` — but no backend
consumes it. The Phase 3 tickets described what EPURE *should* do
under each CAD (BricsCAD: force batch mode + run a setup script;
AutoCAD: activate the "Epure" preferences profile + `_SCRIPT`
invocation in the VBS bridge), but those bullets were deliberately
deferred per the master plan's V2 bullet:

  "EPURE-style user-specific plugin features — keep the spec hook
   but defer the plugin model."

This issue is the deferred work. It is the design-and-land for the
plugin contract itself, with EPURE as the first concrete consumer
so the design has at least one driving use case (a vacuous plugin
model invites yak-shaving; EPURE keeps it honest).

Why this isn't already done
---------------------------

The plugin question splits into three sub-decisions that we have
not yet picked an answer to:

  - **Discovery.** Do plugins live on a search path
    ($ALFE_PLUGIN_PATH, with a default like
    `~/.config/alfe/plugins/`), in a manifest the user passes
    explicitly (`--plugin path/to/plugin.lisp`), or as
    user-installable ASDF systems? The shape of the answer changes
    the install story.
  - **Lifecycle hooks.** What does a plugin get to intercept? The
    minimal set EPURE needs is pre-engine-start (so the bridge can
    activate the profile before run-common.lsp loads), but a future
    plugin might want pre-action / post-action / pre-shutdown.
  - **Per-backend gating.** EPURE has different semantics per CAD —
    BricsCAD forces batch mode, AutoCAD activates a profile,
    clautolisp ignores it. The plugin needs a way to say "I apply
    to backend X only" without each backend having to special-case
    each plugin by name.

V1 left these unanswered intentionally — there was no other plugin
asking for the surface, so over-specifying the model would have
been speculative work. This ticket either makes those calls or
ships a minimal answer that defers them.

In scope
--------

  1. Plugin discovery. Land *one* of:

       a. **File-path plugins.** `--plugin FILE.lisp` loads FILE
          into the alfe image at startup. `$ALFE_PLUGIN_PATH` lists
          fallback directories. The plugin file is a normal Lisp
          source file; it calls `alfe.plugin:register-plugin` to
          hook in.

       b. **ASDF-system plugins.** Plugins ship as
          `alfe-plugin-NAME` ASDF systems on the host's source
          registry; `--plugin NAME` does `(asdf:load-system
          (format nil "alfe-plugin-~A" name))`.

       Decision needed up front. Recommendation: start with (a) —
       it is the smaller surface, matches how DCL/AutoLISP users
       already think about "drop this file in", and (b) can be
       added later by promoting (a)'s register-plugin call into an
       ASDF :perform.

  2. Plugin contract. New package `alfe.plugin` exposing:

       - `register-plugin NAME &key hooks applies-to` — the
         plugin's entry point.
       - `*registered-plugins*` — list of `plugin` structs.
       - Hook names: at minimum :pre-start, :pre-action,
         :post-action, :pre-shutdown.
       - `applies-to`: list of backend keywords
         (`(:bricscad :autocad)`) or `:all`.

     Hook callbacks receive the alfe session struct and a
     hook-specific argument (the action being run, etc.). Errors
     in a hook surface as `backend-bootstrap-error` (for :pre-start)
     or `backend-eval-error` (for action hooks).

  3. EPURE as the first plugin. Ship
     `autolisp-front-end/plugins/epure.lisp` (the canonical
     in-tree example):

       - Reads `*AUTOLISP-EPURE-LSP*` (or a similarly-named env
         var) for the EPURE setup script path.
       - :pre-start under :bricscad — forces batch mode via the
         CLI-options channel, emits the EPURE setup script into the
         workdir, makes run-common.lsp `(load …)` it before the
         main load.
       - :pre-start under :autocad-automation — emits a
         `Profiles.ActiveProfile = "Epure"` line into the VBS
         bridge template (parameterise the template to accept a
         pre-load hook block).
       - :pre-start under :autocad-batch — refuse with a structured
         BACKEND-BOOTSTRAP-ERROR ("EPURE requires the full GUI
         binary; accoreconsole has no profile support") matching
         what alfe-backend-autocad.issue section 4 spelled out.

  4. CLI wiring. `--epure` now triggers
     `(alfe.plugin:request-plugin :epure)` instead of just setting
     `options-epure-p`. The flag stays for compatibility — a future
     ticket can deprecate it in favour of `--plugin epure`.

  5. Spec update. Move the EPURE section in
     `documentation/alfe--specifications.org` from "Out of scope V1"
     to a real section under "Backend bricscad" + "Backend autocad",
     documenting what each backend does when EPURE is active.

  6. Tests:

       - Unit tests for the plugin registry (register / look up /
         walk-hooks-for-backend).
       - A fixture plugin that records each hook it sees, asserts
         the lifecycle order across :pre-start, :pre-action,
         :post-action, :pre-shutdown.
       - EPURE-specific scenarios under
         `tests/scenarios/plugins/epure-*.sexp`: parse the flag,
         emit the right artefacts, refuse under
         `--autocad --mode batch`.
       - Coverage: every option the spec adds for the plugin model
         must be picked up by `make check-spec-coverage`.

Out of scope
------------

  - Plugin sandboxing or untrusted-code protection. V1 of the
    plugin model trusts every loaded plugin; if hardening becomes
    relevant, a separate ticket lands a sandbox.
  - A plugin marketplace / package registry. ASDF + git is enough
    for V2.
  - vlisp-compile as a plugin. It is wedded to AutoCAD automation
    on Windows and does not benefit from the plugin model.

Acceptance criteria
-------------------

  - `--epure --bricscad ...` runs the EPURE setup script before the
    main load. Mock-CAD test asserts the load order.
  - `--epure --autocad --mode batch` exits 4 with the documented
    "EPURE requires the full GUI binary" message.
  - `--plugin path/to/plugin.lisp` loads an arbitrary plugin file
    and the hooks it registers fire at the right lifecycle points.
    Asserted by the fixture-plugin test.
  - `make check-spec-coverage` stays green after the new --plugin /
    --epure semantics land.
  - The EPURE section of the spec exists and matches what alfe
    actually does (no more "deferred" bullets).

Migration note
--------------

The original Phase 3 tickets (now in `issues/closed/`) carried
EPURE bullets that this ticket subsumes. When this ticket lands,
update the "Deferred items" notes in those closed issues to point
at the closing commit.
